{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d7d0d38d-e8e8-4e76-be62-21553cd3913d","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Tests lost history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed how **test IDs** are computed. The fully qualified test name format changed, so Azure DevOps sees every test as brand new. There's no opt-out — you'll lose the historical trend, but results accumulate going forward.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nYour code on **line 13** is the problem:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it isn't associated with any individual test yet. Accessing `TestName` (and other test-scoped properties) now throws. This was always conceptually wrong (class init runs once, not per-test), but v3 silently returned arbitrary/misleading values.\n\n**Fix:** Remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit`, or guard it:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Move per-test logic to [TestInitialize] instead\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`TestContext` property** | Must be declared as `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` (non-nullable). v4 always injects it; null checks are unnecessary. |\n| **Parallelism** | Class-level parallelism is now the **default**. If your tests have shared state, add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or disable it. |\n| **`[DataRow]` display names** | Parameterized test display names changed format, also affecting Azure DevOps history. |\n| **Package consolidation** | The single `MSTest` package (which you're already using) replaces the old `MSTest.TestAdapter` + `MSTest.TestFramework` pair. Don't reference both. |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` for floats** | Tolerance overloads are stricter; some previously-passing comparisons may fail. |\n| **`[DeploymentItem]`** | Paths are resolved differently; verify any file-dependent tests. |\n\nYour project file looks correct — you're on the unified `MSTest 4.1.0` package. The main action item is fixing line 13 in `SetupTests.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f12cf8c2-b555-4c44-becc-736733565916","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I can see the user's specific scenario. Let me provide a comprehensive answer about MSTest v4 breaking changes.\n\nKey issues:\n\n1. **Test ID / Fully Qualified Name changes** — MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed (using fully qualified names differently), which causes Azure DevOps to treat them as new tests with no history.\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a \"class-level\" context, not tied to any specific test. Accessing `TestContext.TestName` will throw because there's no test associated with it at that point. This is a deliberate change in v4.\n   \n3. **Additional breaking changes** — The `TestContext` is now non-nullable with different behavior, `DeploymentItem` works differently, parallelism defaults may have shifted, `DataRow` and `DynamicData` display names have changed, and the unified `MSTest` package now replaces the previous set of separate packages.","outputTokens":899,"requestId":"4C1B:1B1922:1099A74:1430EB4:6A01479E"},"id":"f6a301f7-e1a5-47df-97dd-39f73251ba86","timestamp":"2026-05-11T03:06:27.660Z","parentId":"0116009f-bf4f-4a75-9558-9a25cca193f9"}
